1
00:00:00,154 --> 00:00:01,368
This isn't easy.

2
00:00:01,549 --> 00:00:03,046
<i>Previously on Mad Men...</i>

3
00:00:03,147 --> 00:00:04,280
Sorry I'm late.

4
00:00:05,257 --> 00:00:06,609
Oh... that meeting.

5
00:00:06,750 --> 00:00:08,544
I'm a head of accounts, damn it!

6
00:00:08,890 --> 00:00:10,135
What's gotten into you?

7
00:00:10,320 --> 00:00:11,896
You're supposed to be
calming me down.

8
00:00:12,041 --> 00:00:14,321
- Ted, I've got cancer.
- What?

9
00:00:14,436 --> 00:00:15,592
You gotta call Ted.

10
00:00:17,407 --> 00:00:19,336
<i>They wanted our ideas
and a big agency,</i>

11
00:00:19,465 --> 00:00:20,827
so we gave them both.

12
00:00:20,951 --> 00:00:22,328
We merged.

13
00:00:24,168 --> 00:00:25,772
We have to be careful.

14
00:00:25,906 --> 00:00:27,640
We can't fall in love.

15
00:00:56,149 --> 00:00:58,961
Sync and corrections by n17t01
www.addic7ed.com

16
00:01:07,814 --> 00:01:09,726
_

17
00:01:19,112 --> 00:01:22,647
<i>I don't care, Arnold.
I don't care, just go.</i>

18
00:01:22,682 --> 00:01:26,051
<i>When you get to Minnesota,</i>
<i>tell them what a big deal you are!</i>

19
00:01:26,086 --> 00:01:28,320
<i>Tell them how you don't</i>
<i>listen to anyone</i>

20
00:01:28,355 --> 00:01:30,788
<i>'cause you've got it all</i>
<i>figured out!</i>

21
00:01:30,822 --> 00:01:33,757
<i>"Sylvia,</i>
<i>this is our future."</i>

22
00:01:33,792 --> 00:01:36,794
<i>"Sylvia, anything you want.</i>
<i>Sylvia--"</i>

23
00:01:36,828 --> 00:01:39,263
<i>Guess what, Arnie,</i>
<i>I don't want it.</i>

24
00:01:40,732 --> 00:01:42,566
<i>You have nothing to say?</i>

25
00:01:42,601 --> 00:01:44,435
<i>You're not taking care of me!</i>

26
00:01:44,470 --> 00:01:46,836
<i>You're taking care of you!</i>

27
00:01:46,871 --> 00:01:48,838
<i>Good, leave!</i>

28
00:01:50,508 --> 00:01:52,742
<i>Don't forget to take some money!</i>_

29
00:02:04,854 --> 00:02:06,655
Ted.

30
00:02:07,891 --> 00:02:10,393
First day of school.
You nervous?

31
00:02:10,427 --> 00:02:12,428
What do you think?

32
00:02:12,462 --> 00:02:14,796
It seems silly to ask, but do
you know where you're going?

33
00:02:14,831 --> 00:02:17,099
I'll just follow you.

34
00:02:17,134 --> 00:02:20,435
- Hello, everyone.
- Hey!

35
00:02:20,469 --> 00:02:23,004
Stan, Ginsberg, Ted Chaough.

36
00:02:24,606 --> 00:02:27,042
This is Margie. Margie, Peggy.
Margie, Ted.

37
00:02:27,076 --> 00:02:28,809
It's nice to put
faces with names.

38
00:02:28,844 --> 00:02:30,578
I saw you taking your
little tour the other week

39
00:02:30,612 --> 00:02:31,913
and you looked pretty tall.

40
00:02:31,947 --> 00:02:33,614
But now I see
you're about my height.

41
00:02:33,649 --> 00:02:36,150
I hope you can still
look up to me.

42
00:02:36,184 --> 00:02:39,219
- That was quick.
- Pleasure, Margie.

43
00:02:39,254 --> 00:02:41,621
I've heard a lot about you.
We're all very excited.

44
00:02:44,859 --> 00:02:46,527
Nice knowing you.

45
00:02:52,066 --> 00:02:54,700
John Mathis.

46
00:02:54,734 --> 00:02:56,902
You're in the second office
from reception.

47
00:02:56,937 --> 00:02:59,738
Your secretary will be Connie.

48
00:02:59,773 --> 00:03:03,809
You know my name,
but I don't know yours.

49
00:03:03,843 --> 00:03:05,545
Excuse me, Joan.

50
00:03:05,579 --> 00:03:07,679
Are all the creatives
in one office?

51
00:03:07,713 --> 00:03:11,483
- It's temporary.
- Well, it's going to be very crowded.

52
00:03:11,517 --> 00:03:14,252
But that may change soon.

53
00:03:14,287 --> 00:03:17,689
I know where all
the bodies are buried.

54
00:03:17,723 --> 00:03:20,559
- I need a copy of that.
- They're just notes.

55
00:03:20,593 --> 00:03:22,259
I need a copy
for Mr. Chaough.

56
00:03:22,294 --> 00:03:23,994
He's not going
to change anything,

57
00:03:24,028 --> 00:03:25,596
but he's going to be angry
if I don't know what it is.

58
00:03:25,630 --> 00:03:27,231
Good morning, Moira.

59
00:03:27,265 --> 00:03:30,033
- Joan.
- Good morning.

60
00:03:30,068 --> 00:03:32,936
- Well, hello there.
- Hello.

61
00:03:32,971 --> 00:03:34,805
I'm sorry they didn't
have your office ready yet.

62
00:03:34,839 --> 00:03:36,207
I'll make do.

63
00:03:36,241 --> 00:03:37,708
You know what, Moira?

64
00:03:37,742 --> 00:03:39,509
I'll take care of Miss Olson.

65
00:03:39,543 --> 00:03:41,578
Hopefully you can read
my handwriting.

66
00:03:41,612 --> 00:03:45,381
We're putting you
in Harry's old office.

67
00:03:45,416 --> 00:03:47,917
- Oh.
- But you don't have to share it.

68
00:03:47,951 --> 00:03:49,685
As long as I don't
have to share Phyllis.

69
00:03:49,720 --> 00:03:51,721
Are you okay?

70
00:03:51,755 --> 00:03:53,889
I don't know.

71
00:03:53,924 --> 00:03:56,925
It could be moving boxes
or it could be I slept funny.

72
00:03:58,361 --> 00:04:00,028
Are you still in there?

73
00:04:00,062 --> 00:04:02,464
Yes, everything keeps
changing out here,

74
00:04:02,499 --> 00:04:04,666
but everything's
the same in there.

75
00:04:04,700 --> 00:04:06,101
Except you're a partner.

76
00:04:06,136 --> 00:04:08,403
And you're the copy chief. _

77
00:04:13,108 --> 00:04:14,509
How's your little boy?

78
00:04:14,543 --> 00:04:16,444
He's the man in my life.

79
00:04:16,478 --> 00:04:18,579
- How's yours?
- Oh, he's good.

80
00:04:18,614 --> 00:04:20,414
We bought a building
together to live in.

81
00:04:20,449 --> 00:04:22,983
We bought a building
to live in together.

82
00:04:23,018 --> 00:04:25,419
I'm glad you're here.

83
00:04:25,454 --> 00:04:27,754
Well, I'm glad you're here.

84
00:04:46,139 --> 00:04:48,740
"In addition to the dynamic
press reception

85
00:04:48,775 --> 00:04:51,210
and renewed interest
from Wall Street,

86
00:04:51,244 --> 00:04:56,014
the union of these two agencies
has already brought us victory.

87
00:04:56,049 --> 00:04:58,849
<i>Our congratulations</i>
<i>to Mr. Chaough</i>

88
00:04:58,884 --> 00:05:02,287
<i>and Mr. Gleason for their recent
victory at the Clio Awards</i>

89
00:05:02,321 --> 00:05:06,191
for the one-minute television
commercial 'Little Headaches'

90
00:05:06,225 --> 00:05:11,329
on behalf of St. Joseph's
Children's 'Aspirine.'"

91
00:05:16,367 --> 00:05:18,902
"In closing..."

92
00:05:22,973 --> 00:05:24,608
Well, that's
a beautiful message

93
00:05:24,642 --> 00:05:26,410
to read to our employees,

94
00:05:26,444 --> 00:05:28,111
but perhaps it's best to wait

95
00:05:28,145 --> 00:05:29,813
until we've made all
of the personnel changes.

96
00:05:29,847 --> 00:05:31,380
And you need an ending.

97
00:05:31,415 --> 00:05:34,016
We have a lot
of writers out there.

98
00:05:34,050 --> 00:05:36,619
I'm sorry.
Someone commandeered Clara.

99
00:05:39,623 --> 00:05:41,056
I need a seat.

100
00:05:43,260 --> 00:05:44,827
Don took the last one.

101
00:05:44,861 --> 00:05:47,696
That means you were
here after Don.

102
00:05:47,730 --> 00:05:49,397
Can you see if there's
another chair?

103
00:05:49,432 --> 00:05:51,099
Or you could have my seat.

104
00:05:51,133 --> 00:05:54,068
Yes, thank you.

105
00:05:55,070 --> 00:05:56,504
Moira, take my chair.

106
00:06:08,082 --> 00:06:10,484
Now that we've dispensed
with the gallantry,

107
00:06:10,518 --> 00:06:12,753
Jim Cutler and I have,
we believe, harvested

108
00:06:12,787 --> 00:06:14,388
the gold dusting of the Clios

109
00:06:14,422 --> 00:06:16,323
by arranging for
an advanced introduction

110
00:06:16,358 --> 00:06:17,958
to Fleischmann's Margarine.

111
00:06:17,992 --> 00:06:20,926
They want to be Ted
and Don's first love child.

112
00:06:20,961 --> 00:06:22,729
That's new business.

113
00:06:22,763 --> 00:06:24,930
Isn't there a section of this
meeting called good news?

114
00:06:24,965 --> 00:06:27,767
I never would have taken you
for such a stickler.

115
00:06:27,801 --> 00:06:30,603
Fleischmann's? Groovy.
We'll get right on it.

116
00:06:30,638 --> 00:06:32,805
Regarding ongoing business,

117
00:06:32,839 --> 00:06:35,974
the following is a list of current
accounts in ascending order.

118
00:06:36,008 --> 00:06:37,976
That means smallest to largest,

119
00:06:38,010 --> 00:06:40,712
<i>Chevrolet being excluded</i>
<i>for a separate meeting.</i>

120
00:06:40,747 --> 00:06:42,881
Topaz Pantyhose.

121
00:06:42,915 --> 00:06:44,949
Ken Cosgrove and Burt Peterson.

122
00:06:44,984 --> 00:06:47,452
- And they're thrilled.
- Leica Camera.

123
00:06:47,487 --> 00:06:49,788
Roger and I might
have to go to Germany.

124
00:06:49,822 --> 00:06:52,657
But that's only because
we invited ourselves.

125
00:06:52,691 --> 00:06:54,224
The New York State Thruway.

126
00:06:54,259 --> 00:06:55,493
I just got off the phone

127
00:06:55,527 --> 00:06:56,860
with Henry Lammott
at Mohawk Airlines--

128
00:06:56,895 --> 00:06:58,262
Mohawk's on the next page.

129
00:06:58,297 --> 00:07:00,230
This is related to the Thruway.

130
00:07:00,265 --> 00:07:02,266
Henry Lammott
considers it a conflict,

131
00:07:02,301 --> 00:07:04,635
<i>car travel and air travel</i>
<i>being mortal enemies.</i>

132
00:07:04,670 --> 00:07:07,003
So when Burt Peterson gets ahold
of them, we should resign.

133
00:07:07,037 --> 00:07:09,105
Did you tell Lammott
that was a stretch?

134
00:07:09,139 --> 00:07:11,808
It's a $250,000 media budget.

135
00:07:11,842 --> 00:07:13,343
Mohawk is an airline.

136
00:07:13,377 --> 00:07:16,279
Except, Ted, the client
is New York State

137
00:07:16,314 --> 00:07:18,214
and they gave us
their media buy up front.

138
00:07:18,248 --> 00:07:20,650
- And you already spent it.
- Why didn't you tell us that?

139
00:07:20,685 --> 00:07:24,486
Why didn't you tell us you lost Vicks
for yourself and Clearasil for us?

140
00:07:24,521 --> 00:07:26,622
Why didn't you tell us
Frank Gleason was dying?

141
00:07:26,656 --> 00:07:28,390
Frank's going to be fine.

142
00:07:28,425 --> 00:07:30,659
I know Henry Lammott.

143
00:07:30,694 --> 00:07:32,761
Pete and I will fly up there.

144
00:07:32,796 --> 00:07:34,095
And Ted.

145
00:07:34,130 --> 00:07:35,597
Of course.

146
00:07:35,632 --> 00:07:37,065
What kind of plane do you have?

147
00:07:37,099 --> 00:07:39,200
A Mohawk plane.

148
00:07:39,234 --> 00:07:40,802
Ted's a pilot.

149
00:07:44,272 --> 00:07:45,740
I'll take us up there.

150
00:07:45,774 --> 00:07:47,742
We can land
right outside his office.

151
00:07:50,979 --> 00:07:53,614
- Even better.
- I'm sorry to interrupt.

152
00:07:53,649 --> 00:07:55,449
Mr. Campbell, there's an
urgent phone call for you.

153
00:07:57,084 --> 00:07:58,952
However we're going,

154
00:07:58,986 --> 00:08:01,521
I recommend we go up tomorrow.

155
00:08:06,627 --> 00:08:08,428
What's the next client?

156
00:08:08,463 --> 00:08:11,263
Um, Koss Headphones.

157
00:08:11,297 --> 00:08:13,733
<i>Burt Peterson and Ken Cosgrove.</i>

158
00:08:13,767 --> 00:08:17,035
<i>They sent Burt Peterson</i>
<i>a case of champagne.</i>

159
00:08:18,271 --> 00:08:19,805
Billy?

160
00:08:19,840 --> 00:08:22,274
Mr. Campbell,
I didn't want to trouble you,

161
00:08:22,308 --> 00:08:24,309
but she was--

162
00:08:24,344 --> 00:08:26,845
she's right here.
You want to talk to her?

163
00:08:26,879 --> 00:08:28,346
What happened exactly?

164
00:08:28,381 --> 00:08:30,648
Well, she was banging
on the door pretty hard,

165
00:08:30,683 --> 00:08:32,283
saying she needed
to see your father.

166
00:08:32,317 --> 00:08:34,352
<i>I thought somebody</i>
<i>was gonna call a cop.</i>

167
00:08:34,387 --> 00:08:35,787
May I speak with her?

168
00:08:37,623 --> 00:08:40,258
Bill, you've been so decent,
I hate to ask you another favor,

169
00:08:40,292 --> 00:08:42,593
but could you get her
a G and T with two ice cubes?

170
00:08:42,627 --> 00:08:45,195
- Gin and tonic?
- Yes, if you don't mind.

171
00:08:47,499 --> 00:08:49,266
I don't know what's going on,

172
00:08:49,300 --> 00:08:52,369
but I found this address
on my nightstand

173
00:08:52,404 --> 00:08:54,438
in some woman's handwriting

174
00:08:54,472 --> 00:08:57,073
and I assumed your father
was up to his old tricks.

175
00:08:57,108 --> 00:08:59,275
Mother, he passed away.

176
00:08:59,309 --> 00:09:01,411
You'd like that.
No.

177
00:09:01,445 --> 00:09:03,513
He hasn't been home
for over a week

178
00:09:03,547 --> 00:09:06,048
and his golf clubs
are still at the house.

179
00:09:07,584 --> 00:09:09,118
Mother, you sound confused.

180
00:09:09,152 --> 00:09:10,653
What are you implying?

181
00:09:10,687 --> 00:09:12,655
I want you to relax,
watch the television,

182
00:09:12,689 --> 00:09:14,356
and I will call Bud
to come and get you.

183
00:09:14,391 --> 00:09:16,825
He's going to send
that girl Trudy.

184
00:09:16,859 --> 00:09:19,027
Bud's wife is Judy, not Trudy.

185
00:09:19,061 --> 00:09:22,196
Now I suppose I'm crazy
for mixing those up.

186
00:09:22,231 --> 00:09:23,899
Tell Billy you're fine
on your own.

187
00:09:23,933 --> 00:09:25,467
I am.

188
00:09:38,680 --> 00:09:40,581
Hello there.

189
00:09:40,615 --> 00:09:42,983
Nice to see you, Peggy.

190
00:09:43,017 --> 00:09:44,485
Burt.

191
00:09:44,519 --> 00:09:46,820
We're a long way
from Sterling Cooper.

192
00:09:46,854 --> 00:09:49,288
Looks like the worm has turned.

193
00:09:49,323 --> 00:09:52,625
Well, it's nice to have
the old team back together.

194
00:09:52,660 --> 00:09:55,361
Do you want me to get that?

195
00:09:59,032 --> 00:10:00,232
Hello.

196
00:10:00,267 --> 00:10:03,302
Oh, I was expecting
a secretary.

197
00:10:03,337 --> 00:10:05,104
There isn't one
on the line, is there?

198
00:10:05,138 --> 00:10:07,306
Hold on.

199
00:10:08,976 --> 00:10:10,542
I've got to take this.

200
00:10:10,577 --> 00:10:12,310
Well, we'll have plenty
of time to catch up

201
00:10:12,345 --> 00:10:13,878
on those flights to Detroit.

202
00:10:18,917 --> 00:10:21,586
He's still a cold fish.

203
00:10:24,123 --> 00:10:25,690
Hello.

204
00:10:25,724 --> 00:10:28,193
Come over here now.

205
00:10:28,227 --> 00:10:30,094
I can't.

206
00:10:30,128 --> 00:10:32,463
I have too much
going on in the office.

207
00:10:32,498 --> 00:10:34,231
I need you

208
00:10:34,265 --> 00:10:36,534
and nothing else will do.

209
00:10:40,405 --> 00:10:42,006
Oh.

210
00:10:44,675 --> 00:10:46,142
So?

211
00:10:48,345 --> 00:10:51,114
12:30 at
the Sherry-Netherland.

212
00:10:51,148 --> 00:10:53,483
Call me with a room number.

213
00:10:58,823 --> 00:11:01,056
Come on in, Burt.

214
00:11:02,358 --> 00:11:04,192
Have a seat.

215
00:11:05,194 --> 00:11:07,062
What is this, a bed?

216
00:11:07,096 --> 00:11:08,964
Yeah, you might want
to lie down

217
00:11:08,999 --> 00:11:11,099
because here we are again.

218
00:11:11,134 --> 00:11:14,570
Well, I haven't
forgotten anything.

219
00:11:14,604 --> 00:11:16,572
Not a damn thing.

220
00:11:16,606 --> 00:11:18,840
A lot of times in life
you get to do something

221
00:11:18,874 --> 00:11:20,509
and you don't realize
until it's over

222
00:11:20,543 --> 00:11:22,244
how much you enjoyed it.

223
00:11:22,278 --> 00:11:24,212
And you swear that the
next time it comes around,

224
00:11:24,247 --> 00:11:26,081
you're gonna remember that.

225
00:11:26,115 --> 00:11:27,549
You're right.

226
00:11:27,583 --> 00:11:29,217
And I think I can
work with you, too.

227
00:11:29,252 --> 00:11:31,153
Work?

228
00:11:31,187 --> 00:11:33,754
No, Burt, I'm letting
you go again.

229
00:11:33,788 --> 00:11:36,823
What the hell?
You-- you can't do that.

230
00:11:36,858 --> 00:11:40,694
Probably doesn't make a difference at
this point, but no one fought for you.

231
00:11:40,728 --> 00:11:44,265
Well, we'll see what the folks
at Chevy have to say about this.

232
00:11:44,299 --> 00:11:46,100
Remember Ken Cosgrove?

233
00:11:46,134 --> 00:11:48,969
Like a six-foot version
of Alan Ladd?

234
00:11:49,003 --> 00:11:50,970
He's touring
the plant right now.

235
00:11:51,004 --> 00:11:53,373
You bastard.

236
00:11:53,407 --> 00:11:55,442
I've got four million
in billings.

237
00:11:55,476 --> 00:11:57,877
- What have you got?
- I was thinking you would feel that way.

238
00:11:57,911 --> 00:12:00,813
That you had more clients
and that gives you a voice.

239
00:12:00,847 --> 00:12:04,250
I was imagining you talking
over me in meetings.

240
00:12:04,285 --> 00:12:06,351
Now I don't have that problem.

241
00:12:06,386 --> 00:12:08,387
My clients will leave with me.

242
00:12:08,421 --> 00:12:11,290
No one will ever
say you weren't funny, Burt.

243
00:12:11,324 --> 00:12:13,058
Well, I'll tell you one thing,

244
00:12:13,093 --> 00:12:14,859
I'm expecting some kind
of severance.

245
00:12:14,894 --> 00:12:16,828
Who knows?
We're really hurting.

246
00:12:16,862 --> 00:12:18,997
We're having to cut back.
Well, obviously.

247
00:12:19,031 --> 00:12:20,799
God, you're a real prick,
you know that?

248
00:12:20,833 --> 00:12:23,167
Damn it, Burt,
you stole my good-bye.

249
00:12:32,411 --> 00:12:34,645
Oh, hello.
You must be Burt Peterson.

250
00:12:34,679 --> 00:12:37,414
I'm Bob Benson.
I'm supposed to report to you.

251
00:12:37,448 --> 00:12:39,316
Well, as a first order
